This would be fine, but the scoring system makes frequent errors with sekis between a large unit and a small unit. Always frustrating if a close game could be incorrectly scored due to the AI misdiagnosing seki as death. That said, the app is exclusively offline so this is only ever a real issue against AI, and to that extent, who cares?
replyContent: Thank you for the feedback. Our Go app currently uses the old inaccurate territory/alive and dead estimation as the much more accurate new system was unstable in the early part of the game. We will implement the more accurate system after the middlegame in a future update.

replyContent: A formal rating from CGOS from over 2000 games, allows us to derive a reliable 3 Dan rating for level 10 on an Android phone (www.yss-aya.com/cgos/19x19/bayes.html).Other levels are deliberately weakened and people may find weaknesses that the cpu cannot easily respond to.Also if cpu believes it cannot win, it may make poor moves as all moves lose.

I like the app. I'll talk about the aspects on both sides.  Positive -Interface is good -Computer feels appropriate. Plays good moves. -Nice instructions for new players  What can be improved -Have a board setup option. This would be great for teaching/setting up positions. -Have an option to save games and even export to SGF and review games. -Captured stones are not indicated. This is important for counting.  I could see adding a small icon and number beneath the players' names -In even/handicap games, the komi is indicated as 0 instead of 0.5. -Certain seki positions are incorrectly evaluated. -Have an option so the computer places its stone without the blinking in animation. -When misclicking, it'd be nice to be able to take the moves back faster. Right now, we have to wait for the computer to finish moving before being able to go back. -Computer behavior can be erratic at times. Sometimes it will pass when there are still moves/ataris left. Other times it may place stones inside territory that are clearly dead for it to do so. -This may be a bug, but when receiving a call on my phone, the game can lock up after the call is over. Has only happened once though.  Just my thoughts

content: Best Go app out there.

This is a great app for a beginner like me to practice on. The variety of board sizes and difficulties available is excellent. My biggest gripe is that the app doesn't have an option to record the games you play - I'd like to be able to save the kifu of my games so I can note my progress, but there's no facility for this.

Serious scoring bugs. The app uses the score estimator as the final scoring tool. If the final territory is large, the score estimator will omit a few points of territory. This often leads to the computer missing out on a few points. Also the estimator/final score does not handle some seki correctly. If one color completely surrounds another then the inner group is considered dead even though it's seki. Finally, the AI plays very poorly when lossing. It will not resign so you have to finish a nonsensical game to the very end or abandon the match.
replyContent: Thank you the report. We will introduce a much more accurate scoring system in an update in the near future. If the cpu believes it cannot win, it may make poor moves as all moves lose. This is a property of MTCS, which AlphaGo also uses and causes AlphaGo to play bad moves when losing. We will consider adding cpu resign.

content: The AI is surprisingly strong. Really impressed by how good it is in building moyo and using thickness. Close range fighting is sharp too, but I think sometimes it has trouble determine the life/dead status of big group. I played at the 1 dan level, been having great fun so far. Being able to take back move allowed me to try out different options which has helped in improving my game play.

This app is ok but it certainly doesn't deliver on some critical points. First of all the strength is largely overestimated (I beat the strongest AI and I'm barely 3kyus on KGS, which already overestimate rankings). There's no way this is 3dan. It clearly doesn't know when to resign and makes lots of wrong moves at the very end. Secondly the game doesn't allow to save nor upload games (sgf files), which seems like a very basic feature to have really. One more thing that should be an easy fix is the possibility to choose the komi at the beginning of the game.
replyContent: Program has a formal rating from CGOS, leading to a reliable 3 dan rating for Android phone (see http://www.yss-aya.com/cgos/19x19/bayes.html) but people may find weaknesses that cpu cannot easily respond to and if cpu believes it can't win it may make poor moves as all moves lose. We have added your suggestions for consideration on our to-do list.

The more important problem is that you cannot undo your move while the AI is thinking. I find this very annoying, especially when the AI needs a lot of time.

content: I love this app, and play against it multiple times weekly during this long stint where i am unable to go to the local go club due to work. replyContent: Program has a formal rating from CGOS from 2000+ games, allowing us to derive a reliable 3 Dan rating for an Android phone (see http://www.yss-aya.com/cgos/19x19/bayes.html). Levels are approximate as people may find weaknesses that cpu can't easily respond to. We do not believe that device will affect this but very old devices may have trouble.

content: I've been playing with it for a few weeks now. It is not terribly strong, it starts at 30 kyu at level 1, and at level 10 it is around 15 kyu. We all need to start somewhere, though, and it can be very intimidating playing either other people or programs that are so much stronger than you. It is a good way to get a feel of the game and get stronger until graduating to GoDroid.  Drawbacks that it is impossible to save the games - I have to manually recreate the game on the computer in order to keep a record of it, and I cannot play again until I do if I want to save it. Also, it is impossible to change the komi - it is either 6.5 in the even games or 0 on handicapped games.
Many devices,  including mine,  are designed to be used in landscape orientation.  Non support of this is no longer acceptable.
replyContent: Thank you for your input. We have this for consideration on our to-do list.

content: The AI in this app is quite weak, even on 9x9 games; however I would be willing to look past that if it weren't for the fact that it seems to spill over into the scoring. I've played too many games where the AI had clearly lost (e.g. it had no groups with any eyes) only to have the app trumpet the my opponent had won. Undoing the final passes and starting to killing off the stones eventually gets the AI to wise up, but it gets a little tiresome.
replyContent: Our apologies this did not meet your desired skill level. However we have a new much stronger engine getting ready that will upgrade this app for free.

content: Fun game to learn
One of the most user friendly go apps here. I would estimate its strength about 9k. Try out the free version if you don't need 19x19.
Unlike previous generations of Go AI, this game has no problem beating me.
its literally just a game, all game designers should do this, especially for purchased apps.
Would like to see better scoring and to have a daily download or dictionary for Joseki to help practice better moves for more advanced players
That said, it often has trouble determining life or death during scoring (especially seki). Also no landscape support.
replyContent: Sorry that this did not meet your desired skill level. However we have a new much stronger engine getting ready that will upgrade this app for free. We have added landscape support for consideration on our to-do list.

Compared level by level, it's much weaker than Godroid / GnuGo. (Greatest flaw is that you can often win by not passing: it will fill up it's territory, or waste stones by forming dead groups in your territory.) After two days, i can easily beat it on level 1 and 2 while giving handicaps, but for beginners like me, it's still a good app to start with. Nice plus over Godroid are the statistics, and permanent territory. Good for learning the effects of each move. Bit better GUI than Godroid. Graphics are very good. Five stars if a landscape mode would be added for tablets.
